Example: [typedef_initial_assign.zip](https://github.com/YosysHQ/yosys/files/6702860/typedef_initial_assign.zip)

```shell
$ yosys --version
Yosys 0.9+4081 (git sha1 862e84eb, gcc 10.3.1 -fPIC -Os)
```

## Steps to reproduce the issue

A user defined type declared with an initializer:

```systemverilog
module top_1 (
    input  logic clk,
    input  logic in,
    output logic out
);
  typedef logic user_t;

  user_t var_0 = 0;

  always_ff @(posedge clk) begin
    var_0 <= in;
  end

  assign out = var_0;
endmodule
```

```shell
$ yosys -p "read_verilog -sv -dump_ast2 -dump_vlog2 top_1.sv; prep;"
...
Dumping Verilog AST after simplification:
    module top_1(clk, in, out);
      input clk;
      input in;
      output out;
      (* wiretype = "\user_t" *)
      reg var_0;
      /** AST_TYPEDEF **/
      assign var_0 = 0;
      (* always_ff = 1 *)
      always @(posedge clk)
        var_0 <= in;
      assign out = var_0;
    endmodule
--- END OF AST DUMP ---
...
=== top_2 ===

   Number of wires:                  4
   Number of wire bits:              4
   Number of public wires:           4
   Number of public wire bits:       4
   Number of memories:               0
   Number of memory bits:            0
   Number of processes:              0
   Number of cells:                  1
     $dff                            1
...
```

## Expected behavior

Should be equivalent to:

```systemverilog
module top_2 (
    input  logic clk,
    input  logic in,
    output logic out
);
  typedef logic user_t;

  user_t var_0;

  initial var_0 = 0;

  always_ff @(posedge clk) begin
    var_0 <= in;
  end

  assign out = var_0;
endmodule
```
```shell
$ yosys -p "read_verilog -sv -dump_ast2 -dump_vlog2 top_2.sv; prep;"
...
Dumping Verilog AST after simplification:
    module top_2(clk, in, out);
      input clk;
      input in;
      output out;
      (* wiretype = "\user_t" *)
      reg var_0;
      /** AST_TYPEDEF **/
      initial
        var_0 = 0;
      (* always_ff = 1 *)
      always @(posedge clk)
        var_0 <= in;
      assign out = var_0;
    endmodule
--- END OF AST DUMP ---
...
=== top_2 ===

   Number of wires:                  4
   Number of wire bits:              4
   Number of public wires:           4
   Number of public wire bits:       4
   Number of memories:               0
   Number of memory bits:            0
   Number of processes:              0
   Number of cells:                  1
     $dff                            1
...
```

## Actual behavior

The AST is actually equivalent to:

```systemverilog
module top_3 (
    input  logic clk,
    input  logic in,
    output logic out
);
  typedef logic user_t;

  user_t var_0;

  assign var_0 = 0;

  always_ff @(posedge clk) begin
    var_0 <= in;
  end

  assign out = var_0;
endmodule
```

```shell
$ yosys -p "read_verilog -sv -dump_ast2 -dump_vlog2 top_3.sv; prep;"
...
Dumping Verilog AST after simplification:
    module top_3(clk, in, out);
      input clk;
      input in;
      output out;
      (* wiretype = "\user_t" *)
      reg var_0;
      /** AST_TYPEDEF **/
      assign var_0 = 0;
      (* always_ff = 1 *)
      always @(posedge clk)
        var_0 <= in;
      assign out = var_0;
    endmodule
--- END OF AST DUMP ---
...
=== top_3 ===

   Number of wires:                  4
   Number of wire bits:              4
   Number of public wires:           4
   Number of public wire bits:       4
   Number of memories:               0
   Number of memory bits:            0
   Number of processes:              0
   Number of cells:                  0
...
```

